{% if template == "webapp-static-pwa" %}
This is a static Vite + TypeScript PWA scaffold that keeps production serving zero-backend while shipping a manifest, service worker, and icon placeholders by default.

Use this when installability and offline app-shell behavior are part of the baseline contract.

Choose `webapp-static` for a simpler static site without PWA defaults. Choose `webapp-ssr-vite` or `webapp-ssr-next` when request-time SSR still matters.

Selection guidance:

- Choose `webapp-static` when all you need is static hosting and client rendering, with no install/offline requirement.
- Choose `webapp-static-pwa` when the browser owns the long-lived state and you want offline app-shell behavior, install metadata, and zero-backend delivery by default.
- Choose SSR only when the HTML must depend on request-time inputs such as auth, cookies, headers, crawler-visible content, or other server-owned data.

SSR and hash-persisted client state do not mix well:

- URL-hash state and browser-only persistence are invisible to the server on first render.
- If that state materially changes the initial view, SSR has to guess, then patch on hydration, which creates avoidable mismatch complexity.
- Prefer the static or static-PWA templates when the client is the true owner of persisted hash/local state.

Dev mode with HMR:

```bash
pnpm dev
```

Offline and install surface included in the scaffold:

- `public/manifest.webmanifest`
- `public/service-worker.js`
- `public/icons/icon-192.svg`
- `public/icons/icon-512.svg`

The client entry registers the service worker immediately and includes a one-time takeover reload path so offline navigation works after the first successful install/activation.

Local-origin validation flow:

```bash
pnpm build
pnpm run preview -- --host 127.0.0.1 --port 4173
```

- Validate install and offline behavior from `http://127.0.0.1:4173`, not `file://...`.
- Visit once while online so the service worker installs and precache materializes.
- Then switch the browser to offline mode and confirm reload plus in-app navigation still serve the app shell.
- If the app uses wasm or web workers, confirm those requests are same-origin and still succeed offline after the online warm-up visit.

Production build via Buck (Nix under the hood):

```bash
buck2 build //projects/apps/{{ name }}:app
```

Static runtime asset guidance:

- Keep wasm producers on the generated module-contract path and let the shared static precache flow pick up their emitted runtime assets.
- Keep worker entrypoints inside the Vite build so they emit hashed same-origin assets that the service worker can cache safely.
- Do not hand-maintain service-worker cache lists for wasm or worker files.

The same local-workspace TypeScript dependency and wasm watcher contract from `webapp-static` remains in place.
